# Emily FastAPI API Rules

## Request / Response
- Pydantic v2 `BaseModel` for every request and response schema — no raw dicts on the wire
- Use `Field(...)` with descriptions for auto-generated OpenAPI docs
- Return type annotations on all route handlers

## Routing
- One `APIRouter` per resource domain with `prefix` and `tags`
- Route files in `api/routes/` — import and `app.include_router()` in `api/app.py`
- Consistent naming: `POST /api/v1/chat/stream`, `GET /api/v1/models`

## Lifecycle
- Use lifespan context managers (`@asynccontextmanager` + `app = FastAPI(lifespan=...)`)
- Never use deprecated `@app.on_event("startup")` / `@app.on_event("shutdown")`
- Clean up httpx clients, DB connections, and provider caches in lifespan shutdown

## SSE Streaming
- Return `StreamingResponse(generate(), media_type="text/event-stream")` with `Cache-Control: no-cache` and `X-Accel-Buffering: no`
- Use Emily's `_sse_event(event, data)` helper: `f"event: {event}\ndata: {json.dumps(data)}\n\n"`
- Always emit a final `event: done` so the client knows the stream ended cleanly
- For OpenAI-compatible SSE, include `stream_options: {"include_usage": True}` in the request body

## Error Handling
- Raise `HTTPException` with structured `detail` (string or dict) — never return raw 500s
- Wrap generator bodies in `try/except` and yield an `event: error` SSE before returning
- Log exceptions with `log.exception(...)` via structlog — never `print()`

## Middleware & Security
- CORS configured in `api/app.py` — explicit `allow_origins`, never `["*"]` in production
- Auth via `EMILY_API_SECRET` env var checked in middleware — not in each route
- Rate limiting middleware for public-facing endpoints

## Performance
- All route handlers must be `async def` — use `asyncio.to_thread` for any sync library call
- Use FastAPI `BackgroundTasks` for fire-and-forget work (DB writes after response)
- Lazy-import heavy modules inside route handlers to avoid slowing app startup

## Database
- Access the shared `ConversationDatabase` via `get_chat_db()` — never construct directly in routes
- All DB calls are async (`aiosqlite`) — never call sync SQLite from async routes
- Wrap multi-step DB operations in a transaction
